#love‚ù§Ô∏è

To the people who say GPA don‚Äôt matter, yall need to stop spreading false information because it is more nuanced than just GPA dont matter as a whole.

GPA is correlated with career success. E.g. higher GPA = more opportunities to accelerate career growth (internships, scholarships)

What GPA does NOT do is determine with 100% certainty you will be successful in life or perform very well on the job.

However, on average (tendency), people with higher GPA will be more successful and perform well on the job because intrinsically they are hardworking and goal-oriented.

Now, for those with low GPA, it is not the end of the world. You are not 100% condemned to a life of peasantry. Instead u might just have a slightly harder time but if luck favours you or decide to finally work hard, you will achieve the same success as a high GPA person.

Note: Luck is not luck entirely, it is about creating more opportunities for you to be lucky.

(I am a grad, trust my words or not, its uty)

as someone who‚Äôs battled suicidal thoughts for years too, things do get better. it might not be tomorrow, next week, or even next year, but give yourself some time to heal. find out what the things making you unhappy are & slowly find a way to get through them. the same way, look at your past & find something that made you happy despite everything else. i found joy in a past ocsp, so i pushed myself to live to feel that happiness again. i believe you‚Äôll find something you like too.

i know it‚Äôs tough to see life from a positive perspective now & the ‚Äúlittle things‚Äù don‚Äôt keep you going anymore, but that‚Äôs okay for now. even if you think nobody cares about you, you should push on & live until you find the one who cares.

life is different for everyone, so this might just be your long chapter of battles w depression & suicidal thoughts. trust that a better time will come to you in the near future.

in the meantime, keep pushing. i believe in you.

#adviceüó£Ô∏è

I'm gonna play devil's advocate and say that choosing btn NUS and SMU cs is not as black and white as ppl think.

NUS is obv more academically rigorous and technical, but it's also more stressful and time-consuming. Culture in NUS cs can be more discouraging as well. The other differences are the wider array of specialisations in NUS, availability of hall and the lecture-tutorial vs seminar style teaching.

Uni should be about going for what you think you'll thrive in and what will personally support you with the most benefits, not simply going for the 'popular' option. Go figure

#A12300035 | SMU Confess Channel | Post confession

14:50
#studies‚úçüèº

I think personally, the main question you should be asking yourself is this: What is the main outcome you envision out of the years that you spend in a university?

With that question in mind, you should then proceed to prioritise the factors that will influence your university years the most (e.g. curriculum rigour, distance to school, learning methods) and then choose the university which aligns the most with you.

Regarding the SMU SCIS curriculum, although the choices and options available might be limited compared to other schools, there exists the UResearch programme which allows you to work with professors to research and explore areas within computing to enhance your knowledge outside of the school syllabus.

P.S.: I am one of the SCIS students currently at WQ/Millennium; for me, my choice back then was to enjoy Bricklanes every week before it closed down (-:

HIDDEN SMU LORE: PART VI (Part V at #R01020123)

Just when it seemed like Captain Rizzles had solidified his quirky reign over SMU, a new and formidable figure arrived: Lily Kong, also known as The Domitrix. Unlike Captain Rizzles, who thrived on spontaneity and fun, Lily was all about precision, order, and discipline. With a reputation for running the most rigorous student circles, she was determined to challenge the chaos that Captain Rizzles had brought to campus.

Lily wasn‚Äôt impressed by Captain Rizzles‚Äô antics‚Äîno amount of LeBron Maid Costumes or scavenger hunts would win her over. Her mission was clear: SMU needed structure, and she was just the one to bring it.

Her first entrance to a council meeting was enough to make any student pause. No quirky dances, no wild outfits‚Äîjust Lily in a sharp black suit, leather briefcase in hand, exuding an authority that made even the loudest students silent. She wasted no time in addressing the group. ‚ÄúEnough of the chaos,‚Äù she stated firmly. ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs time to bring order. SMU needs leadership that is serious, not just fun.‚Äù

Captain Rizzles, never one to back down from a challenge, shot back with his signature grin. ‚ÄúOrder? How boring! Let‚Äôs throw a campus-wide talent show‚Äîsurprise performances in the library!‚Äù he suggested, clearly excited by his own idea.

And so, the battle was set: Chaos vs. Control. Captain Rizzles continued to plan outrageous events‚Äîflash mobs, surprise talent shows, and spontaneous competitions‚Äîwhile Lily fought back with carefully planned debates, strategic study groups, and a strict code of conduct for students.

The campus was divided. Who would win‚ÄîCaptain Rizzles‚Äô fun-loving unpredictability or The Domitrix‚Äôs ironclad discipline? Whatever the outcome, one thing was clear: SMU would never be the same.

re: whether or not to skip class for overseas CNY gatherings

it depends on
1) do you actually want to see the extended family or not
(if you don't want to see them then hooray! you have a free "need to focus on uni studies ü§ì" get out of jail card and don't feel guilty about using it)

and also,
2) how much of the time will be spent w. family (ie do you have time to do other leisure things if you want to have a break)
3) (if you still get angpao) whether or not your relatives will still give angpao c/o your parents, and how important that angpao is to you
4) is it actl gg to affect you if you miss the class?

tbh CNY is q early this year, it's in week 3 so if you actl want to see your relatives then I encourage you to go! classes aren't that important in the big scheme of things üíï

if you want to enjoy time with each other, it shouldn't only be one person who pays. and in a longer term situation, you and your partner are a team and that means you both put in effort

You don't have to be that attractive to get girls to go on dates, its just about not being a creep. Why not approach first dates as just trying to get to know people? For 1 to 1 dates, offer coffee/brunch (cos i mean coffee chats are already very common, and if they don't go well its only like 45min - 1hr). Don't need to be too forward before the first date cos you don't even fully know the person.

And really impressing a girl is not particularly difficult. Two key traits
- Drive / Ambition: If you aren't the most career centric person, that's fine. But at least show you can be passionate about something (a hobby, a sport etc.). Show proof that you aren't lazy. Being well-groomed generally helps in this regard.
- Care / Concern: Be a kind person. Like genuinely want to find out more about what the girl likes, show you care about her interests etc.

If you meet and like there are stark differences (e.g., religion, lifestyle choices etc.) in which a compromise is difficult, move on~ But just because you met a girl who didn't like you, don't suddenly become an incel cos of it.

I had first dates being pretty fat (BMI of 28+, i have dropped it since then for health reasons), i'm 100% not good looking, have 0 fashion sense (jeans, polo t, no watch etc.), no car to drive girls around (MRT is great, at most grab). My job on dating apps was also a joke (cos really only IRAS needs to know my salary, and i didn't want to go out with people who assumed i would pay for everything - cos i can but i rather save my money for things like housing).

#love‚ù§Ô∏è

I'm the OP of the long message recommending coffee dates, also happily in a r/s right now with a stellar GF. Both of us are also in high finance.

I recommend coffee dates because amongst my female friends, many of which are very high flying (by salary) in consulting, IB or tech - most making 8k+ base. The whole coffee / brunch date idea was a framework designed by, you guessed it, ladies who i consider ultra eligible. The big reason why coffee dates aren't a "cop out" is that for people like that, time is their greatest asset. Why should anyone, both the guy or the girl waste time on someone they obviously feel no connection with? 45 mins - 1h means that either party can LEAVE if they feel it wont work out. If it does work out, a coffee date can lead to dinner, a brunch date can lead to lunch + tea time. Its the optionality that makes these shorter dates so attractive.

For a guy, its also less daunting. What if the date doesn't go well? Even my IB / Quant guy friends don't necessarily want to drop 100 - 200 on a nice restaurant for a random girl (they can MORE than afford it). They would rather spend it on friends etc.

So people who talk about good investments? Yes, i think my female friends are great investments. But they're also looking for guys who understand that their time is precious, and that they don't need to be wowed by money since they're more than financial independent.
